<!-- INTERESTS -->

<h2>Interests</h2>

<ul>

<li>Exploring impact of AI on the <a href="https://ericprhodes.com">future of work</a> &#x2014; how adoption is really an organizational design problem (second-order effects, incentives, power, and agency)</li>

<li>Using human-centered design methodologies (UX, CX, service design) to make emerging tech <a href="https://legacy.secondrealm.com/posts/technourishment/">more humane</a></li>

<li>Making connections and understanding the <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/the-art-of-interdisciplinary-thinking">Interdisciplinary</a> relationships between <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/my-artistic-foundations">seemingly</a> <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/on-becoming-a-designer">unrelated</a> philosophies, topics, and ideas</li>

<li>Creating <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/when-art-became-social">Networked art</a> and exploring internet culture <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/the-speed-of-art%2C-memes-and-value-in-web3">as a medium</a> and the weird new <a href="http://legacy.secondrealm.com/posts/zombie-futurism/">aesthetics</a> and <a href="https://legacy.secondrealm.com/posts/trash-art-history/">behaviors</a> it produces</li>

<li><a href="https://legacy.secondrealm.com/posts/cryptopunks-copyright-legal-experts/">Digital ownership</a> and <a href="https://paragraph.com/@epr/nothing-is-original">remix culture</a>—art law, IP, CC0, and decentralized systems (blockchain/Web3) as experiments in coordination and meaning</li>

<li>Yankees, <a href="https://baseballanalytics.com/best-baseball-analytics-books/">baseball analytics</a>, <a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/homelab/">home labs</a>, fantasy <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A_Discovery_of_Witches_(TV_series)">series</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Magicians_(American_TV_series)">with</a> <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Horror_Story:_Coven">witches</a>, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Art_of_the_Steal_(2009_film)">art heist documentaries</a>, <a href="https://www.subwayalumni.com/1988-national-championship/">Notre Dame football</a>, and college sports in general</li>

</ul>

<hr />


<!-- THREADS I'M PULLING ON -->
<section class="threads">
  <h2>Threads I'm Pulling On</h2>
  <p>Free-range exploration&#x2014;open-ended concepts I'm exploring sparked by patterns I notice in the world, without the weight of a defined goal or specific outcome.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <a href="/humanities" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Humanities in the Era of Agentic AI</a>: As AI absorbs repeatable work, the differentiators become more human, sensemaking, judgment, communication, empathy, and navigating social dynamics alongside technical complexity.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/cultural-residue" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Cultural Residue in a Digital World</a>: What's left after a moment passes, the traces that survive and carry meaning later (ephemera, errata, and marginalia). What I'm chasing is what happens to that residue in a digital world where things don't decay or disappear the same way, they persist but become buried, unsurfaced, and functionally missing, and where the “original moment” can keep existing in full form, changing how we remember, revisit, and move on.
    </li>
    <li>
      <a href="/improving-emotional-literacy-through-art" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Improving Emotional Literacy Through Art</a>: A way of using art to get better at noticing and naming what I’m actually feeling. The idea is to map emotions onto visual and symbolic forms (color, flowers, simple motifs) so my emotional vocabulary gets more precise. It blends journaling, a bit of mindfulness, digital art-making, and emotional intelligence research into a practical way to understand and express complicated emotions.
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>

<hr />

<!-- SHORT BIO -->

<section class="short-bio">

<h2>Me, in 60 Seconds</h2>

<p>Creative technologist, systems thinker, and digital artist. Designing and building across multiple waves of technological innovation&#x2014;social platforms and smartphones, connected devices and assistants, crypto/Web3 (blockchain and NFTs), and now LLMs and agentic AI.</p>

<p>Background in human-centered design, customer experience, user research, digital strategy, support/operations, and startup advising. Undergraduate degrees in industrial relations and computer science with extended studies in visual arts. Graduate research on AI adoption and the future of work.</p>

<p>The through-line is a restless, polymathic curiousity for where socio-technical complexity meets human behavior. I focus on how emerging tech can improve the human experience, and on the work of integrating it mindfully in the real world. The stakes just keep rising.</p>

